# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1929-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1929-world-series/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1929-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1929-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1929-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1929-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1929-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1929-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1929-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1929-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1929-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1929-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1929-world-series/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1929-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1929-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1929-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1929-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1929-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1929-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] The **1929 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball for the 1929 season.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] The 26th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that pitted the American League (AL) champion Philadelphia Athletics against the National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] The Athletics defeated the Cubs in five games to win the Series.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] This was the first World Series game ever played at Wrigley Field.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Because seven of the eight regulars in the Cubs' lineup hit right-handed, Athletics manager Connie Mack started only right-handed pitchers during the series and kept all his left-handed pitchers in the bullpen, even though two of his best starters, Lefty Grove and Rube Walberg, were left-handed.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] The Athletics' Howard Ehmke, who started his major league career in 1915, had been a good starting pitcher, but by 1929, he was suffering from a sore arm.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Pitching only occasionally, he finished the regular season with a 7–2 record, a 3.29 earned run average, and 20 strikeouts in 54.2 innings.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Meanwhile, the Athletics had a big lead in the AL standings.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] In August, Mack told Ehmke that he was going to be released after the season.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Ehmke accepted the decision but said that he would like to pitch in a World Series game, having never done so before.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] In mid-September, with both league pennant races wrapped up, Mack had Ehmke leave the team and go on the road to scout the NL champion Cubs for the last few weeks of the season, telling him to be prepared to start game 1 of the World Series.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Mack kept the pitching decision a secret until the day of the game.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] The Athletics had plenty of good pitchers available, and players on both teams were surprised that Ehmke was starting.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] However, with his knowledge of the Cubs' batters and a rested arm, Ehmke pitched a complete game, winning 3–1 with no earned runs allowed and 13 strikeouts.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] The strikeout total broke the World Series record that had been set by Ed Walsh in 1906; Ehmke's record then stood until it was broken by Carl Erskine in 1953.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] This ended up being the last win of Ehmke's career and also became one of the most famous games in baseball history.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Attending the game was nine-year-old John Paul Stevens, who would grow up to become a Supreme Court Justice.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Behind the pitching of George Earnshaw and Grove, the Athletics won 9–3 and took a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Jimmie Foxx became the first player to homer in his first two World Series games.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Al Simmons also homered and had four runs batted in.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Game 3 was a pitchers' duel that featured many tense moments.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Guy Bush won this game for the Cubs' only victory, holding the Athletics to one run despite allowing nine hits and two walks.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Earnshaw started his second straight game for the Athletics and allowed only one earned run himself.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Sticking to his right-handed-pitchers-only policy, Mack again made a risky move in Game 4 by starting 46-year-old Jack Quinn.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Unlike Ehmke, however, Quinn was no challenge to the Cubs' hitters, who scored seven runs off him before Mack pulled him in the sixth inning.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Trailing 8–0, the Athletics then scored 10 runs in the bottom of the seventh inning and won the game.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] In the middle of the rally that became known as the "Mack Attack", Cubs center fielder Hack Wilson lost Mule Haas's fly ball in the sun, and Haas circled the bases for a three-run inside-the-park home run, bringing the Athletics to within a run at 8–7.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] This was the last inside-the-park home run in a World Series game until Game 1 of the 2015 World Series.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] The eight-run deficit overcome by the Athletics is still the largest in postseason history.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Art Nehf's relief pitching appearance in this game was his last in the major leagues.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Mack gave Ehmke his second start of the Series, but without the advantage of surprise, he was less effective, touched for two runs, and taken out in the fourth inning.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] The Athletics trailed 2–0 going into the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] However, Haas tied the game up with a two-run homer.
[src:1929-world-series/1929-world-series] Then, after a double by Simmons and an intentional walk to Foxx, Bing Miller's double scored Simmons to give the Athletics their first World Series championship in 16 years.
